<HEADLINE>
DOMESTIC VIOLENCE LAW TO APPLY TO COHABITANTS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 5 (CNA) 03/06/07  11:00:06 (By Y.C. Jou)
</P>
<P>
The Domestic Violence Prevention Act will soon apply to couples
who are cohabiting, including gay lovers, thanks to amendment
passed the legislature Monday.
</P>
<P>
The act, enacted in 1998, currently designates domestic violence
as violence occurring between certain categories of family
members, current or former. This amendment expands the scope of
the law's application to include people currently or formerly
cohabiting.
</P>
<P>
Among changes described by lawmakers asepoch-makingwas a change
of emphasis in the law fromimproving harmony in the family
topreventing violence.
</P>
<P>
An overhaul of the law at the eve of Women's Day (March 8) is the
greatest gift for women, said Democratic Progressive Party
lawmaker Huang Shu-ying. She said the amended law better meets
the needs of society today.
</P>
<P>
The amendment  offers  more extensive  injunctions  against
perpetrators of violence in order to better protect their
victims.
</P>
<P>
It also requires local governments to join efforts with the
police, social workers and civil affairs units to set up domestic
violence prevention centers to provide services offering 24-hour
rescue, injury diagnosis and shelter.
</P>
